	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)">Office of <persName>Davis&#44; Peixotto &#38; Co.</persName></p>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Nos. 3 &#38; 5 Water Street</placeName>.</p>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Corner of Superior Street</placeName>.</p>
				<p><persName>Geo. A. Davis</persName>.</p>
				<p><placeName>NEW YORK</placeName>.</p>
				<p><persName role="author">B. F. Peixotto</persName>.</p>
				<p><placeName>CLEVELAND</placeName>.</p>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Cleveland</placeName>&#44; <date>Nov 15th 1865</date>.</p>
				<p>My dear &#38; Rev Friend</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Thanks for your letter<lb/> of the <date>13th</date> and the earnest spirit you<lb/> exhibit in behalf of <placeName>Israel</placeName> and the<lb/> Order.  No earthly triangle can<lb/> equal the joy Heaven and the life<lb/> immortal beyond the tomb will give<lb/> you.  Your richest reward will come<lb/> alas&#33; like that of every great benefac<lb/>&#45;tor after &#8220;life&#39;s fitful fever is over.&#8221;<lb/>  When the spirit has departed to<lb/> &#8220;the <del>it</del> undiscovered country from<lb/> whose frame<add>&#63;</add> no traveller returns.&#8221;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Would to God all men entered<lb/> into the spirit of your labors&#44; ap&#45;<lb/>&#45;preciated and valued them as<lb/> I do.  Would it were that my<lb/> worldly means were such as<lb/> to field you that support<lb/> which wd give you the &#8220;ample</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>margin&#8221; for the realization of all your<lb/> aspirations in behalf of <placeName>Israel</placeName>&#8212;in<lb/> the name and for the sake of <placeName>Israel&#39;s</placeName><lb/> God.  Be of cheerful heart dear<lb/> Friend&#44; The future will be just to you<lb/> even if the present be ungrateful<lb/> and indifferent.  &#8220;The labor we<lb/> delight in physics pain&#8221; else would<lb/> we of<del>f</del>t throw aside those things<lb/> which in their personal relation<lb/> to us are rather &#8220;ills&#8221; than<lb/> &#8220;benefits.&#8221;  We must bear the &#8220;whips<lb/> and scorns of time&#8221; the &#8220;proud man&#39;s<lb/> <sic>continuely</sic>&#8221; the &#8220;insolence of office&#8221;<lb/> and &#8220;the spurns that patient<lb/> merit of the unworthy taker&#45;&#8221;<lb/> and nobly breast the tide of<lb/> outrageous fortune&#8212;the seas<lb/> of trouble that ever and<lb/> none beat against our<lb/> rock bound&#8212;&#40;heart felt&#41;<lb/> ribs&#8212;&#40;brain and soul&#41;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">To be disheartened&#8212;to give way<lb/> is to field up the &#8220;good fight&#8221; and</p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p>&#8220;perish quickly&#44; <add>&#63;</add>&#33;&#8221;  To <hi rend="underline">me</hi> should these<lb/> consoling words be uttered rather<lb/> than to <hi rend="underline">you</hi>.  For have you not withstood<lb/> all these throes of time and fate&#63;<lb/>  Have you not tasted the bitter cup<lb/> and yet survived its draught&#44; to live<lb/> a life more blessed&#63;  Heaven hath<lb/> been with you still&#44; and your heart is<lb/> yet ambient in its effulgent love for<lb/> the noble cause espoused five and<lb/> twenty years ago.  And though it<lb/> be as <persName>Byron</persName> hath it&#8212;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">&#8220;Years still fire from the brain<lb/> As vigor from the limb<lb/> And life&#39;s enchanted cup<lb/> But sparkles near the brim&#8221;<lb/> Yet to age there comes no &#8220;chilling<lb/> frost&#8221; if the heart be warm and<lb/> the spirit steadfast.  There is &#8220;a<lb/> green youth in age&#8221; that makes of<lb/> it a holy and a blessed time.<lb/>  Please Heaven such be thine for<lb/> eye&#33; Xxx I have sent the recp<lb/> to <persName>Miss L &#38; W</persName>.  I will take the</p>
			<pb n="4"/>
				<p>copy of the Pentateuch &#64; &#36;25 the<lb/> price you name.  I will try to dispose<lb/> of the other books now that I know<lb/> their value.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I have sent &#40;<date>Sunday</date>&#41;<lb/> a list of the Lodges that up<lb/> to that time had reported<lb/> &#40;I had not yours of the <date>13th</date> then&#41;<lb/> to <placeName>N. Y.</placeName> for publication.  You<lb/> will see them mentioned in<lb/> the &#8220;Messenger&#8221; and if it<lb/> so please you add to the<lb/> list those you have given<lb/> me &#40;except Har Nevoh&#41; which<lb/> I noticed in the <hi rend="underline">Occident</hi> as<lb/> having acted and publish<lb/> in the best of Jewish Periodicals<lb/> your own paper.  I will<lb/> be gratified&#44; or if you prefer<lb/> <hi rend="underline">wait</hi> till all returns are<lb/> in and then let me<lb/> have 2 or 3 pages to<lb/> write up &#38; I will</p>
				<p>In haste</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">With Sincerest wishes</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">for your health &#38; happiness</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">your Friend &#38; Bro</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">B. F. Peixotto</persName></p>
				<p><addressee>Rev I. Leeser</addressee>. <placeName>Phila.</placeName></p>
